def Mileage_to_num(Mileage):
    """In the Mileage column I'm replacing the terminal 'km/kg' and kmpl with
    the empty string and converting to a float. Non-strings are 
    np.nans and are kept as np.nans."""
    if isinstance(Mileage, str):
      
        if 'km/kg' in Mileage:
            return float(Mileage.replace('km/kg', ''))
        elif 'kmpl' in Mileage:
            return float(Mileage.replace('kmpl', ''))

    elif isinstance(Mileage, float):
        return Mileage                
    else:
        return np.nan


def Engine_to_num(Engine):
    """In the Engine column I'm replacing the terminal 'cc' with
    the empty string and converting to a float. Non-strings are 
    np.nans and are kept as np.nans."""
    if isinstance(Engine, str):
        return float(Engine.replace('CC', ''))
    elif isinstance(Engine, float):
        return Engine
    else:
        return np.nan

def Power_to_num(Power):
    """In the Power column I'm replacing the terminal 'bhp' with
    the empty string and converting to a float. Non-strings are 
    np.nans and are kept as np.nans."""
    if isinstance(Power, str):
        return float(Power.replace('bhp', ''))
    elif isinstance(Power, float):
        return Power    
    else:
        return np.nan

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(20, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

  • Year has a positive correlation with number of seats and the price of the car.

  • Year has a negative correlation with Kilometers driven and price of new car.

  • Price has a positive correlation with how many seats are in the car and the price of the car when it was new. This means the used cars will be more expensive the more expensive it was as a new car, and the more seats it has, which is expected.

  • Price also has a positive correlation with the power and volume engine of the car, suggesting that the the used cars with more power and engine volume will sell at a higher price.

  • Price has a negative correlation with kilometers driven and mileage which means the price of the car goes down as the number of kilometers driven or mileage increases, which is expected.

  • Price has a positive correlation with the year of the car. This is somewhat expected as it suggests that the newer used car sells for more than the older used car.

Outlier treatment with the Z-Score

In [130]:
def z_transform(x):
    return (x - np.mean(x)) / np.std(x)

np.random.seed(1)
x1 = np.random.normal(size=1000)
x2 = np.random.lognormal(size=1000)


plt.hist(z_transform(x1))
plt.title('z-transformed normal data')
plt.show()


plt.hist(z_transform(x2))
plt.title('z-transformed lognormal data')
plt.show()

The z-scores fall between the -3 and 3 which is considered usual.

Feature Engineering

Summary of EDA

Data Description

  • The target variable (Price) is of float type
  • Columns like Mileage, Engine, and Power that should be float type are of object type
  • Columns like Year, Kilometers_Driven, Seats, and New_Price are numerical columns
  • The remaining columns are of object type
  • There are 3 duplicates values in the data
  • A few columns have missing values in the data

Data Cleaning:

  • The serial number (S.No) and location were dropped as their values were not considered useful to the analysis
  • Mileage, Engine, and Power were converted from object to float.
  • The missing values in the data are treated as follows: Price was dropped because it was the target variable Missing values in Mileage were inputed with Median Missing values in Power were inputed with Median Missing values in Engine were inputed with Mean

Observation from EDA Listed under each figure

Model performance check¶

In [143]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Observations

  • The train and test $R^2$ are 0.88 and 0.09, indicating that the model explains 88% and 9% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively. Also, both scores are not comparable.

  • RMSE values on the train and test sets are also not comparable.

  • This shows that the model is overfitting.

  • MAE indicates that our current model is able to predict used car value within a mean error of 1.6 on the test set.

  • MAPE of 114.06 on the test data means that we are able to predict within ~ >100% of the used car value.

  • I have been unable to build a predictive model that can be used by the used car company to predict the value of a used car.
  • This model can't be used to predict the value of a used car
